<collectingCountry id="F30A764EFFA4FF99EB414699E043FE15" box="[1295,1384,404,429]" name="Mexico" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, and along the Chilean coastline. However, based on the frequency of occurrence of this species in&gt; 500 
<collectionCode id="ED0CAE1BFFA4FF99EAB646B5E01EFE68" box="[1272,1333,440,464]" country="Australia" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">DNA</collectionCode>
samples, 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D5DFFA4FF99EED946D0E419FE4D" authorityName="Underkoffler &amp; Luers &amp; Hyde &amp; Craig" authorityYear="2018" box="[151,306,476,501]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Lampridae" genus="Lampris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lampriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="563" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="megalopsis">
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99EED946D0E419FE4D" box="[151,306,476,501]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">L. megalopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only rarely found east of 160°W.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3076555FFA4FF99EE89450DE13BFD1F" pageId="12" pageNumber="563" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA236DEFFA4FF99EE89450DE797FD85" blockId="12.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99EE89450DE465FDAF" bold="true" box="[199,334,512,536]" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is taken from the Greek 
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99ED28450CE688FDA0" box="[870,931,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">mega</emphasis>
, meaning, “big or large”, and 
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99EB44450CE01AFDA0" box="[1290,1329,513,536]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">ops</emphasis>
meaning “eye” in reference to its comparatively large eye.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA236DEFFA4FF99EE89454AE13BFD1F" blockId="12.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99EE89454AE464FDD8" bold="true" box="[199,335,583,608]" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">Coloration.</emphasis>
In dead specimens (unpreserved), body steel grey on dorsal surface fading to bright silver on ventral surface. Irregular white spots distributed over entire body, head, and chest. Fins deep red. In preserved specimens, body dark grey with spots and median fins appearing yellowish tan.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3076555FFA4FF99EE8945B9E684FC80" pageId="12" pageNumber="563" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA236DEFFA4FF99EE8945B9E684FC80" blockId="12.[151,1437,151,824]" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99EE8945B9E410FD73" bold="true" box="[199,315,692,716]" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D5DFFA4FF99EF0F45B8E708FD75" authorityName="Underkoffler &amp; Luers &amp; Hyde &amp; Craig" authorityYear="2018" box="[321,547,692,717]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Lampridae" genus="Lampris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lampriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="563" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="megalopsis">
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99EF0F45B8E708FD75" box="[321,547,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">Lampris megalopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D5DFFA4FF99ECA245B8E655FD74" authorityName="Underkoffler &amp; Luers &amp; Hyde &amp; Craig" authorityYear="2018" box="[748,894,693,716]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Lampridae" genus="Lampris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lampriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="563" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="incognitus">
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99ECA245B8E655FD74" box="[748,894,693,716]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">L. incognitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with which it shares a small portion of its range. The most obvious difference is in the size of the eye. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D5DFFA4FF99ED5945D4E69FFD48" authorityName="Underkoffler &amp; Luers &amp; Hyde &amp; Craig" authorityYear="2018" box="[791,948,727,752]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Lampridae" genus="Lampris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lampriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="563" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="megalopsis">
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99ED5945D4E69FFD48" box="[791,948,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">L. megalopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the horizontal eye diameter is typically&gt; 5.0 % FL and is contained ~4.7 times in head length. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D5DFFA4FF99ED4B45F0E6BCFCAC" authorityName="Underkoffler &amp; Luers &amp; Hyde &amp; Craig" authorityYear="2018" box="[773,919,765,788]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Lampridae" genus="Lampris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lampriformes" pageId="12" pageNumber="563" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="incognitus">
<emphasis id="B969EACCFFA4FF99ED4B45F0E6BCFCAC" box="[773,919,765,788]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="563">L. incognitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the horizontal eye diameter is typically &lt;5.0 % FL and vertical eye diameter is contained ~5.4 times in head length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
